Notebook[{
Cell["Tropical Convexity (graph-translated)", "Title",ExpressionUUID->"c3f18c7a-2218-44bc-b1eb-cbbbaeeaa34c"],

Cell["\<\
The graph translation of tropical convexity in (R^n)_min: tropical segments, \
geodesically convex sets, the convex hull. This is sense 2 of \"tropical\" in \
the literature -- the convex-figure side of the picture (Maclagan and \
Sturmfels, Develin and Sturmfels) -- as opposed to sense 1, the min-plus \
arithmetic on scalars and matrices (TropicalPlus, TropicalDot, ...) covered \
in the TropicalOperations layer. Both senses are graph-side here: this layer \
never instantiates loci in (R^n)_min directly; instead it recovers the same \
combinatorial structure on graphs.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"ff6b9545-a2ac-4758-acb9-f057224f7749"],

Cell["\<\
The reading: under the shortest-path metric, a tropical segment between two \
graph vertices is the vertex set of any geodesic between them; a geodesically \
convex set is one closed under FindSegment; the geodesic convex hull is the \
smallest such superset. The first tropical axiom T1 -- existence of a \
tropical segment between any two points -- becomes equivalent to \
ConnectedGraphQ.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"6e638baa-c5b6-4057-8e5d-29b519eb6779"],

Cell["Setup", "Section",ExpressionUUID->"08d7376a-8376-4299-aae8-fcbf13c6b039"],

Cell["Needs[\"WolframInstitute`SyntheticInfrageometry`\"]", "Code",ExpressionUUID->"65dbbf5e-e1c0-44df-8ead-8808838bedf0"],

Cell["Postulates", "Section",ExpressionUUID->"f15198e8-af44-4ad4-be14-83ff65b9cd46"],

Cell["\<\
FindTropicalSegment -- enumerate tropical segments from u to v as sorted \
vertex sets.\
\>", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"7db339a6-1376-4222-ab0c-b5c68f53ba47"],

Cell["\<\
FindGeodesicConvexHull -- the smallest geodesically convex superset of a \
vertex set.\
\>", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"020cd0c2-b156-4f48-b722-de90a44080de"],

Cell["Predicates", "Section",ExpressionUUID->"9edc2480-0279-4c5f-a5c9-d89782fb3808"],

Cell["\<\
TropicalSegmentQ -- test whether a vertex set realises a tropical segment \
from u to v.\
\>", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"44704c44-bbf2-4581-9987-904739f03869"],

Cell["\<\
GeodesicallyConvexQ -- test whether a vertex set is closed under FindSegment.\
\
\>", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"03889784-ef53-43e8-a6da-009f087e042f"],

Cell["\<\
UniqueTropicalSegmentQ -- test whether the tropical segment from u to v is \
single-valued.\
\>", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"c1ccfc7c-5000-4ba6-b10d-c0f18cc8946a"],

Cell["\<\
TropicalT1Q -- test the first tropical axiom: every two vertices admit a \
tropical segment (= ConnectedGraphQ).\
\>", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"e2660e3e-196b-4c8c-b065-5daa4f60a6f5"],

Cell["Connection to the TropicalOperations layer", "Section",ExpressionUUID->"5095c65a-e8f0-41fe-882a-41cb63e92f1f"],

Cell["\<\
The two senses of \"tropical\" are graph-side companions, not duplicates.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"29a5ce77-4272-4493-91a8-8e87c1346637"],

Cell["\<\
Sense 1 (TropicalOperations): TropicalPlus / TropicalTimes / TropicalDot / \
TropicalMatrixPower live on numbers and matrices in the min-plus semiring. \
The bridge to graphs is TropicalMatrixPower[A, k] === GraphDistanceMatrix[g] \
for k >= diameter (where A is the cost-adjacency matrix); the matrix-form \
triangle inequality is TropicalDot[D, D] === D.\
\>", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"05dbdd02-aaec-454e-ad28-0fd9ea292868"],

Cell["\<\
Sense 2 (this layer): tropical segments, hulls, T1 are read off geodesic \
structure on the graph itself. The link to the matrix layer is via the \
metric: a vertex set S is geodesically convex iff S x S satisfies the \
tropical-idempotence relation under the restricted distance matrix.\
\>", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"629142c8-6d8f-4250-bbb4-c88186a458b1"],

Cell["Tutorial", "Section",ExpressionUUID->"c0ca12d7-d9ec-4d07-bd92-151ba419e812"],

Cell["See TropicalConvexityTutorial for runnable examples.", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"61c0bc82-f982-4379-89fd-0200edaa9cb1"],

Cell["See also", "Section",ExpressionUUID->"550f43c7-589d-49eb-a039-c3ab267ca0cc"],

Cell["\<\
TropicalOperationsGuide -- the algebraic min-plus operations on numbers and \
matrices.\
\>", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"6de906cd-7160-491e-abd5-a13223d03984"],

Cell["\<\
MetricAlgebraGuide -- MetricInterval, GeodesicCount, the \
distance-multiplicity matrix, MedianVertices.\
\>", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"5a911a90-3d1f-4195-b575-0577dc4c4a10"],

Cell["\<\
EuclideanLayerGuide -- FindSegment, the underlying geodesic enumeration.\
\>", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"640635df-af8c-46e0-87aa-86cb3d546f25"],

Cell["References", "Section",ExpressionUUID->"3806ecc1-4d34-4f31-bd30-423bb9cf35f1"],

Cell["\<\
Maclagan and Sturmfels, Introduction to Tropical Geometry, AMS GSM 161, 2015, \
https://janos.cs.technion.ac.il/COURSES/238900-13/Tropical/MaclaganSturmfels.\
pdf\
\>", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"2353f743-87b0-42fa-ad1c-d35d6a6bc0f8"],

Cell["\<\
Develin and Sturmfels, Tropical Convexity, Documenta Math. 9, 1-27, 2004, \
https://arxiv.org/abs/math/0308254\
\>", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"f4c89f87-85c1-4a2a-b83e-6fb6f78bd81d"],

Cell["\<\
van der Pol, A Tropical Approach to the Median, in Combinatorial Convexity \
(Bjorner, Linial, eds.), 2009 (median-graph background).\
\>", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"c181c6da-704c-4790-a60d-27af63501dbd"],

Cell["\<\
Mulder, The Interval Function of a Graph, Mathematical Centre Tracts 132, \
Amsterdam 1980 (foundational treatment of geodesic convexity on graphs).\
\>", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"029f2a41-ad37-4478-8c25-9d5910e36b06"]
},
